{"title_page": "William Blair Bruce", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = William Blair Bruce\n| image            = William Blair Bruce.jpg\n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1859|10|08}} \n| birth_place      = [[Hamilton, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1906|11|17|1859|10|08}}\n| death_place      = [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n| resting_place    = \n| nationality      = Canadian\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = Brucebo\n| notable_works    = ''The Phantom Hunter''\n| style            = [[Impressionism]]\n| movement         = \n| spouse           = [[Carolina Benedicks-Bruce]]\n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = {{URL|https://www.brucebo.se/}}\n}}\n\n'''William Blair Bruce''' (8{{nbsp}}October 1859{{snd}}17{{nbsp}}November 1906) was a Canadian painter. He studied in France and became one of Canada's first [[Impressionism|impressionist]] painters. He lived most of his life in France and on the island of [[Gotland]], Sweden, where he and his Swedish wife [[Carolina Benedicks-Bruce]] created the artists estate [[Brucebo]], which was later established as a [[nature reserve]].\n\n== Biography ==\n=== Early years ===\nWilliam Blair Bruce was born on 8{{nbsp}}October 1859, in [[Hamilton, Ontario]], Canada,<ref name=Historica /> where he grew up in Corktown and on the Mountain.<ref name=haggo>{{cite web|last1=Haggo|first1=Regina|title=Hamilton's most famous painter comes home|url=http://www.thespec.com/whatson-story/4537163-hamilton-s-most-famous-painter-comes-home/|website=www.thespec.com|publisher=[[The Hamilton Spectator]]|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> A plaque in Bruce Park, Hamilton marks the site of his childhood home.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Alan L|title=William Blair Bruce 1859-1906|url=http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques/Plaque_Hamilton52.html|website=www.ontarioplaques.com|publisher=Ontario's Historical Plaques|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> He was the son of William Bruce, born 1833 in Scotland, who emigrated to Hamilton with his wife Janet Blair<ref name=toronto />  in 1837.<ref name=chronology>{{cite web|last1=Lundgren|first1=Jan|title=Benedicks\u2013 Bruce Chronology 1856 \u2013 1935|url=http://bruceboscholarshipsc.ipage.com/?page_id=57|website=www.bruceboscholarshipsc.ipage.com|publisher=Brucebo Scholarships|date=January 2010|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> Initially Bruce studied law at Hamilton Collegiate Institute,<ref name=toronto /> but had his mind set on becoming an architect,<ref name=SLU /> and studied for a while at the Mechanics Institute in Hamilton, in 1877. He worked for an architectural firm for the ensuing two years.<ref name=AGH /> Members of his family were both musically and artistically inclined<ref name=toronto /> and noticed Bruce's talent at an early age. In 1881, they sent him to [[Paris]] to study, a journey that extended over the years. He would only return to Canada on two short occasions.<ref name=AGH>{{cite web|last1=Lundgren|first1=Jan O.|editor=Bill Manson|title=The Bruce-Benedicks Saga and the Birth of the AGH|url=http://www.artgalleryofhamilton.com/aa_brucebo.php|website=www.artgalleryofhamilton.com|publisher=[[Art Gallery of Hamilton]]|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Paris ===\n[[File:William Blair Bruce Friluftsatelje cropped.jpg|thumb|left|''Open air studio'', 1885&ndash;90]]\nIn Paris his classical education at [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] included [[Genre art|genre scenes]] and many other subjects.<ref name=Historica>{{cite web|title=William Blair Bruce|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/william-blair-bruce|website=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|publisher=[[Historica Canada]]|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref> Like many other artists of the time he wanted to experience the Parisian art scene and join in the competition to exhibit at the annual [[Salon (Paris)|Salon]] in Paris.<ref name=AGH /> He also traveled to the [[Barbizon school|artist colony]] in [[Barbizon]] where he and a group of artist friends rented a cottage in 1882,<ref name=AGH /> and [[Grez-sur-Loing]] where a new generation of Swedish artists, such as [[Carl Larsson]], his wife [[Karin Berg\u00f6\u00f6 Larsson|Karin Berg\u00f6\u00f6]], [[Bruno Liljefors]] and [[August Strindberg]] had formed a colony.<ref name=grez>{{cite web|title=Venez \u00e0 Grez! Venez \u00e0 Grez!|trans-title=Come to Grez! Come to Grez!|url=http://www.artistes-grezsurloing.fr/|website=www.artistes-grezsurloing.fr|publisher=Associations de Grez-sur-Loing|accessdate=13 July 2015|language=French}}</ref> He became acquainted with [[Impressionism]] and ''[[En plein air]]'' or \"outdoors painting\", a style he came to prefer working with. He also became one of Canada's first impressionist painters.<ref name=into>{{cite web|last1=Jeffrey|first1=Robyn|title=Into The Light: The Paintings of William Blair Bruce at the Art Gallery of Hamilton|url=http://www.ngcmagazine.ca/correspondents/into-the-light-the-paintings-of-william-blair-bruce-at-the-art-gallery-of-hamilton|website=www.ngcmagazine.ca|publisher=[[National Gallery of Canada]]|date=25 August 2014|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> Bruce exhibited at the Salon in 1882. His works received positive reviews but the following year his self confidence and finances deteriorated. His parents were not entirely enthusiastic about his new painting style but he ignored them and began to create very large paintings. His ''Temps Pass\u00e9'' was exhibited at the 1884 Salon<ref name=into /> although despite this success he remained in financial difficulties.<ref name=toronto>{{cite web|title=Bruce, William Blair|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/bruce_william_blair_13E.html|website=www.biographi.ca|publisher=[[University of Toronto]]|accessdate=13 July 2015}}</ref> Bruce subsequently suffered a nervous breakdown and hastily returned to Canada for the first time.<ref name=toronto /> To compound his problems, the steamship ''Brooklyn'', carrying about 200 of his works, sank outside [[Anticosti Island]] in the [[Gulf of Saint Lawrence]] on 8{{nbsp}}November 1885.<ref name=toronto /><ref name=AGH />\n\nIn the summer of 1885, Bruce had met the Swedish sculptor Carolina Benedicks in France. They fell in love and when Bruce returned to Canada, she made a surprise visit accompanied by her uncle, to persuade him to return to Paris. They were engaged in the autumn of 1886, and returned to Europe in 1887.<ref name=AGH />\n{{clear}}\n\n== Return to Europe ==\n[[File:Carolina Benedicks-Bruce and William Blair Bruce.jpg|thumb|upright|Carolina Benedicks-Bruce and William Blair Bruce]]\nBruce returned to France a bolder artist. In 1887, he and a group of fellow artists such as the American painter Theodore Robinson, travelled to Giverny where they shared a house and,influenced by Monet who lived nearby, painted a number of impressive impressionist sketches {{<ref name= William H. Gerdts, \"The Most Beautiful Country That I Have Ever Visited:\" William Blair Bruce in Giverny,\" Into the Light: The Paintings of William Blair Bruce (1859-1906), Art Gallery of Hamilton, 2014, pp. 108-126.)/>}} In 1888, on his return to Paris, he painted ''The Phantom Hunter'', which became an instant success at the Salon and marked the peak of his career.<ref name=into /> He and Benedicks married at the British embassy in Stockholm on 5{{nbsp}}December the same year.<ref name=riks /><ref name=toronto /> She provided energy and stability for Bruce throughout his life and also became his favorite model.<ref name=toronto />\n\nIn May 1889, the couple returned to Grez and Bruce wrote to his mother that \"Gr\u00e8z {{sic}} is a great improvement on Barbizon, quite a different country in fact\". A month later, Bruce also sold some paintings to the American artist [[Walter Gay]], who was visiting Grez at the time. Bruce and Benedicks-Bruce continued to make annual visits to Grez up until 1894. They rented a small house, which had previously been the home of Carl Larsson and his wife Karin. It was here that Bruce painted his ''Open-Air Studio'' (now in the [[Nationalmuseum|National Museum of Fine Arts]], Stockholm). It is a view from their home in Grez, picturing Benedicks-Bruce doing an etching out-doors behind a sun screen. In 1895, the couple made a brief journey to Hamilton in Canada,<ref name=americans>{{cite book|last1=Salus|first1=Carol|title=Out of Context: American Artists Abroad|date=2004|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]|location=Westport,CT|isbn=0-313-31649-X|page=55|edition=8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8FfyNjE373UC&printsec=copyright&hl=sv#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> where Bruce painted on the [[Six Nations of the Grand River First Nation|Six Nations Reserve]].<ref name=toronto /> Throughout the 1890s, they led a bohemian life, travelling to Capri, Italy and Sweden where they took a liking to Gotland and its light.<ref name=AGH />\n\nIn 1900\u201306, the couple created a summer home called Brucebo (Swedish for: \"The house where Bruce lives\") on Gotland.<ref name=americans /> Here, Bruce painted, did some amateur [[archaeology]] and socialized with the locals, while Benedicks-Bruce worked with sculptures and etchings as well as tended the garden and the many animals she had gathered at Brucebo.<ref name=SLU /><ref name=AGH />\n\nBruce died suddenly on 17{{nbsp}}November 1906 in [[Stockholm]] at the age of 47,<ref name=Historica /> and Benedicks-Bruce settled down permanently at Brucebo.<ref name=riks>{{cite encyclopedia |last=M\u00f6rner|first=Stellan G.|encyclopedia=Svenskt biografiskt lexikon|title=Carolina M Benedicks-Bruce|url=http://sok.riksarkivet.se/sbl/Presentation.aspx?id=18472 |access-date=12 July 2015 |language=Swedish|date=1922|publisher=[[National Archives of Sweden]]|volume=3|pages=162}}</ref> After Bruce's death, a commemorative exhibition of 122 of his works was held in Paris in 1907.<ref name=toronto /> Carolina donated 29 of his paintings to the City of Hamilton. This donation became the foundation of the [[Art Gallery of Hamilton]] that opened in 1914.<ref name=haggo /> Even though Bruce enjoyed a good reputation towards the end of his life with 15 participations at the Salon, exhibitions in [[London]], [[Toronto]], Stockholm, [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]] and came to influence many young artists in Canada,<ref name=ljus>{{cite web|last1=Molin|first1=Maria|title=Att f\u00e5nga Brucebos ljus|trans-title=To capture Brucebo's light|url=http://www.gotland.net/se-och-gora/arkiv/att-fanga-brucebos-ljus|website=www.gotland.net|publisher=Gotlands Media AB|date=17 July 2014|accessdate=12 July 2015|language=Swedish}}</ref> he remains {{as of|2015|lc=y}} relatively unknown. A large part of his production can be seen at Brucebo, which is now a museum managed by the Brucebo Foundation.<ref name=toronto />\n\nBenedicks-Bruce stayed at Brucebo until her death on 16{{nbsp}}February 1935.<ref name=gun>{{cite web|last1=Westholm|first1=Gun|title=Carolina Benedicks Bruce|url=http://www.gotland.net/sv/att-gora/carolina-benedicks-bruce|website=www.gotland.net|publisher=Gotlands Media AB|accessdate=12 July 2015|language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n== Brucebo ==\n{{main|Brucebo}}\nOriginally used as a summer house by Bruce and his wife, they rebuilt and extended Brucebo in 1900\u201306 into their permanent home and studio.<ref name=ljus /> In 2009, the estate was converted into an art museum. In connection to this, a shooting occurred at the main house.<ref name=ilska>{{cite web|last1=Leino|first1=Per|title=All ilska riktades mot ordf\u00f6randen|trans-title=All anger was directed at the chairman|url=http://www.helagotland.se/start/?articleid=4555245|website=www.helagotland.se|publisher=Helagotland.se|accessdate=13 July 2015|date=2 December 2008|language=Swedish}}</ref> The museum and the estate are managed by the Brucebo Foundation.<ref name=SLU>{{cite web|last1=Sv\u00e4nnel|first1=Jessica|title=V\u00e5rdprogram f\u00f6r tr\u00e4dg\u00e5rden p\u00e5 Brucebo|url=http://jessicasvannel.se/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/V%C3%A5rdprogram-f%C3%B6r-Brucebo_12juni14_JessicaSv%C3%A4nnel.pdf|website=www.jessicasvannel.se|publisher=[[Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences]]|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> The foundation also grants scholarship to younger Canadian artists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brucebo and W.B. Bruce Fine Art Scholarships for Canadian Artists|url=http://www.swedenabroad.com/en-GB/Embassies/Ottawa/Study-in-Sweden/Scholarships/Brucebo-and-WB-Bruce-Fine-Art-Scholarships-2012-2013/|website=www.swedenabroad.com|publisher=[[List of diplomatic missions in Ottawa|Embassy of Sweden, Ottawa]]|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> In 1970, the {{convert|35|ha|km2|abbr=on}} Brucebo estate was established as a nature reserve.<ref name=blair>{{cite web|title=En William Blair kommer hem|trans-title=A William Blair comes home|url=http://www.lansstyrelsen.se/gotland/Sv/nyheter/2011/Pages/en-william-blair-kommer-hem.aspx?keyword=brucebo+naturreservat|website=www.lansstyrelsen.se|publisher=The County Administrative Boards of [[Gotland County]]|accessdate=14 July 2015|date=8 April 2011|language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" widths=\"180\" heights=\"140\">\nFile:Brucebo salong.jpg|Brucebo artist's home, room with Bruce's portrait of his wife\nFile:Brucebo atelje s\u00f6der.jpg|The south part of the studio in Brucebo, Benedicks-Bruce's ''L'obs\u00e8de'' (left, back), ''Michel Angelo'' and bust of Bruce (right, front)\nFile:Brucebo atelje.jpg|The studio in Brucebo, Bruce's self portrait (left) and full figure portrait of his wife\nFile:Brucebo indianrummet.jpg|The \"Indian room\" at Brucebo with paintings from the Six Nations Reserve\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book\n| last1=Bruce\n| first1=William Blair\n| year=1982\n| title=Letters home, 1859\u20131906: the letters of William Blair Bruce\n| last2=Murray\n| first2=Joan\n| authorlink2=Joan Murray (art historian)\n| publisher=Penumbra Press\n| isbn=978-0-920806-36-4\n| url-access=registration\n| url=https://archive.org/details/lettershome185910000bruc\n}}\n\n*{{cite book \n|last1=Facos \n|first1=Michelle \n|editor-last=Bruce \n|editor-first=Tobi \n|title=Into the Light: The Paintings of William Blair Bruce (1859-1906) \n|date=2014 \n|publisher=Art Gallery of Hamilton, 2014 \n|isbn=1907804528 \n|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=HS8cngEACAAJ&dq=Into+the+Light:+The+Paintings+of+William+Blair+Bruce+(1859+-+1906).&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQqNDExNboAhXGOpoKHTcSArEQ6AEIKDAA\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|William Blair Bruce}}\n*[http://jessicasvannel.se/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/V%C3%A5rdprogram-f%C3%B6r-Brucebo_12juni14_JessicaSv%C3%A4nnel.pdf Maps, pictures and a presentation of Brucebo] (in Swedish)\n\n{{Canadian Impressionism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bruce, William Blair}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1906 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian male painters]]\n[[Category:People from Hamilton, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Canadian Impressionist painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in Sweden]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = William Blair Bruce\n| image            = William Blair Bruce.jpg\n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1859|10|08}} \n| birth_place      = [[Hamilton, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1906|11|17|1859|10|08}}\n| death_place      = [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n| resting_place    = \n| nationality      = Canadian\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = Brucebo\n| notable_works    = ''The Phantom Hunter''\n| style            = [[Impressionism]]\n| movement         = \n| spouse           = [[Carolina Benedicks-Bruce]]\n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = {{URL|https://www.brucebo.se/}}\n}}\n\n'''William Blair Bruce''' (8{{nbsp}}October 1859{{snd}}17{{nbsp}}November 1906) was a Canadian painter. He studied in France and became one of Canada's first [[Impressionism|impressionist]] painters. He lived most of his life in France and on the island of [[Gotland]], Sweden, where he and his Swedish wife [[Carolina Benedicks-Bruce]] created the artists estate [[Brucebo]], which was later established as a [[nature reserve]].\n\n== Biography ==\n=== Early years ===\nWilliam Blair Bruce was born on 8{{nbsp}}October 1859, in [[Hamilton, Ontario]], Canada,<ref name=Historica /> where he grew up in Corktown and on the Mountain.<ref name=haggo>{{cite web|last1=Haggo|first1=Regina|title=Hamilton's most famous painter comes home|url=http://www.thespec.com/whatson-story/4537163-hamilton-s-most-famous-painter-comes-home/|website=www.thespec.com|publisher=[[The Hamilton Spectator]]|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> A plaque in Bruce Park, Hamilton marks the site of his childhood home.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Alan L|title=William Blair Bruce 1859-1906|url=http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques/Plaque_Hamilton52.html|website=www.ontarioplaques.com|publisher=Ontario's Historical Plaques|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> He was the son of William Bruce, born 1833 in Scotland, who emigrated to Hamilton with his wife Janet Blair<ref name=toronto />  in 1837.<ref name=chronology>{{cite web|last1=Lundgren|first1=Jan|title=Benedicks\u2013 Bruce Chronology 1856 \u2013 1935|url=http://bruceboscholarshipsc.ipage.com/?page_id=57|website=www.bruceboscholarshipsc.ipage.com|publisher=Brucebo Scholarships|date=January 2010|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> Initially Bruce studied law at Hamilton Collegiate Institute,<ref name=toronto /> but had his mind set on becoming an architect,<ref name=SLU /> and studied for a while at the Mechanics Institute in Hamilton, in 1877. He worked for an architectural firm for the ensuing two years.<ref name=AGH /> Members of his family were both musically and artistically inclined<ref name=toronto /> and noticed Bruce's talent at an early age. In 1881, they sent him to [[Paris]] to study, a journey that extended over the years. He would only return to Canada on two short occasions.<ref name=AGH>{{cite web|last1=Lundgren|first1=Jan O.|editor=Bill Manson|title=The Bruce-Benedicks Saga and the Birth of the AGH|url=http://www.artgalleryofhamilton.com/aa_brucebo.php|website=www.artgalleryofhamilton.com|publisher=[[Art Gallery of Hamilton]]|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Paris ===\n[[File:William Blair Bruce Friluftsatelje cropped.jpg|thumb|left|''Open air studio'', 1885&ndash;90]]\nIn Paris his classical education at [[Acad\u00e9mie Julian]] included [[Genre art|genre scenes]] and many other subjects.<ref name=Historica>{{cite web|title=William Blair Bruce|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/william-blair-bruce|website=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|publisher=[[Historica Canada]]|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref> Like many other artists of the time he wanted to experience the Parisian art scene and join in the competition to exhibit at the annual [[Salon (Paris)|Salon]] in Paris.<ref name=AGH /> He also traveled to the [[Barbizon school|artist colony]] in [[Barbizon]] where he and a group of artist friends rented a cottage in 1882,<ref name=AGH /> and [[Grez-sur-Loing]] where a new generation of Swedish artists, such as [[Carl Larsson]], his wife [[Karin Berg\u00f6\u00f6 Larsson|Karin Berg\u00f6\u00f6]], [[Bruno Liljefors]] and [[August Strindberg]] had formed a colony.<ref name=grez>{{cite web|title=Venez \u00e0 Grez! Venez \u00e0 Grez!|trans-title=Come to Grez! Come to Grez!|url=http://www.artistes-grezsurloing.fr/|website=www.artistes-grezsurloing.fr|publisher=Associations de Grez-sur-Loing|accessdate=13 July 2015|language=French}}</ref> He became acquainted with [[Impressionism]] and ''[[En plein air]]'' or \"outdoors painting\", a style he came to prefer working with. He also became one of Canada's first impressionist painters.<ref name=into>{{cite web|last1=Jeffrey|first1=Robyn|title=Into The Light: The Paintings of William Blair Bruce at the Art Gallery of Hamilton|url=http://www.ngcmagazine.ca/correspondents/into-the-light-the-paintings-of-william-blair-bruce-at-the-art-gallery-of-hamilton|website=www.ngcmagazine.ca|publisher=[[National Gallery of Canada]]|date=25 August 2014|accessdate=12 July 2015}}</ref> Bruce exhibited at the Salon in 1882. His works received positive reviews but the following year his self confidence and finances deteriorated. His parents were not entirely enthusiastic about his new painting style but he ignored them and began to create very large paintings. His ''Temps Pass\u00e9'' was exhibited at the 1884 Salon<ref name=into /> although despite this success he remained in financial difficulties.<ref name=toronto>{{cite web|title=Bruce, William Blair|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/bruce_william_blair_13E.html|website=www.biographi.ca|publisher=[[University of Toronto]]|accessdate=13 July 2015}}</ref> Bruce subsequently suffered a nervous breakdown and hastily returned to Canada for the first time.<ref name=toronto /> To compound his problems, the steamship ''Brooklyn'', carrying about 200 of his works, sank outside [[Anticosti Island]] in the [[Gulf of Saint Lawrence]] on 8{{nbsp}}November 1885.<ref name=toronto /><ref name=AGH />\n\nIn the summer of 1885, Bruce had met the Swedish sculptor Carolina Benedicks in France. They fell in love and when Bruce returned to Canada, she made a surprise visit accompanied by her uncle, to persuade him to return to Paris. They were engaged in the autumn of 1886, and returned to Europe in 1887.<ref name=AGH />\n{{clear}}\n\n== Return to Europe ==\n[[File:Carolina Benedicks-Bruce and William Blair Bruce.jpg|thumb|upright|Carolina Benedicks-Bruce and William Blair Bruce]]\nBruce returned to France a bolder artist. In 1887, he and a group of fellow artists such as the American painter Theodore Robinson, travelled to Giverny where they shared a house and, influenced by Monet who lived nearby, painted a number of impressive impressionist sketches {{(see William H. Gerdts, \"The Most Beautiful Country That I Have Ever Visited:\" William Blair Bruce in Giverny,\" Into the Light: The Paintings of William Blair Bruce (1859-1906), Art Gallery of Hamilton, 2014, pp. 108-126.)}} In 1888, on his return to Paris, he painted ''The Phantom Hunter'', which became an instant success at the Salon and marked the peak of his career.<ref name=into /> He and Benedicks married at the British embassy in Stockholm on 5{{nbsp}}December the same year.<ref name=riks /><ref name=toronto /> She provided energy and stability for Bruce throughout his life and also became his favorite model.<ref name=toronto />\n\nIn May 1889, the couple returned to Grez and Bruce wrote to his mother that \"Gr\u00e8z {{sic}} is a great improvement on Barbizon, quite a different country in fact\". A month later, Bruce also sold some paintings to the American artist [[Walter Gay]], who was visiting Grez at the time. Bruce and Benedicks-Bruce continued to make annual visits to Grez up until 1894. They rented a small house, which had previously been the home of Carl Larsson and his wife Karin. It was here that Bruce painted his ''Open-Air Studio'' (now in the [[Nationalmuseum|National Museum of Fine Arts]], Stockholm). It is a view from their home in Grez, picturing Benedicks-Bruce doing an etching out-doors behind a sun screen. In 1895, the couple made a brief journey to Hamilton in Canada,<ref name=americans>{{cite book|last1=Salus|first1=Carol|title=Out of Context: American Artists Abroad|date=2004|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]|location=Westport,CT|isbn=0-313-31649-X|page=55|edition=8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8FfyNjE373UC&printsec=copyright&hl=sv#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> where Bruce painted on the [[Six Nations of the Grand River First Nation|Six Nations Reserve]].<ref name=toronto /> Throughout the 1890s, they led a bohemian life, travelling to Capri, Italy and Sweden where they took a liking to Gotland and its light.<ref name=AGH />\n\nIn 1900\u201306, the couple created a summer home called Brucebo (Swedish for: \"The house where Bruce lives\") on Gotland.<ref name=americans /> Here, Bruce painted, did some amateur [[archaeology]] and socialized with the locals, while Benedicks-Bruce worked with sculptures and etchings as well as tended the garden and the many animals she had gathered at Brucebo.<ref name=SLU /><ref name=AGH />\n\nBruce died suddenly on 17{{nbsp}}November 1906 in [[Stockholm]] at the age of 47,<ref name=Historica /> and Benedicks-Bruce settled down permanently at Brucebo.<ref name=riks>{{cite encyclopedia |last=M\u00f6rner|first=Stellan G.|encyclopedia=Svenskt biografiskt lexikon|title=Carolina M Benedicks-Bruce|url=http://sok.riksarkivet.se/sbl/Presentation.aspx?id=18472 |access-date=12 July 2015 |language=Swedish|date=1922|publisher=[[National Archives of Sweden]]|volume=3|pages=162}}</ref> After Bruce's death, a commemorative exhibition of 122 of his works was held in Paris in 1907.<ref name=toronto /> Carolina donated 29 of his paintings to the City of Hamilton. This donation became the foundation of the [[Art Gallery of Hamilton]] that opened in 1914.<ref name=haggo /> Even though Bruce enjoyed a good reputation towards the end of his life with 15 participations at the Salon, exhibitions in [[London]], [[Toronto]], Stockholm, [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]] and came to influence many young artists in Canada,<ref name=ljus>{{cite web|last1=Molin|first1=Maria|title=Att f\u00e5nga Brucebos ljus|trans-title=To capture Brucebo's light|url=http://www.gotland.net/se-och-gora/arkiv/att-fanga-brucebos-ljus|website=www.gotland.net|publisher=Gotlands Media AB|date=17 July 2014|accessdate=12 July 2015|language=Swedish}}</ref> he remains {{as of|2015|lc=y}} relatively unknown. A large part of his production can be seen at Brucebo, which is now a museum managed by the Brucebo Foundation.<ref name=toronto />\n\nBenedicks-Bruce stayed at Brucebo until her death on 16{{nbsp}}February 1935.<ref name=gun>{{cite web|last1=Westholm|first1=Gun|title=Carolina Benedicks Bruce|url=http://www.gotland.net/sv/att-gora/carolina-benedicks-bruce|website=www.gotland.net|publisher=Gotlands Media AB|accessdate=12 July 2015|language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n== Brucebo ==\n{{main|Brucebo}}\nOriginally used as a summer house by Bruce and his wife, they rebuilt and extended Brucebo in 1900\u201306 into their permanent home and studio.<ref name=ljus /> In 2009, the estate was converted into an art museum. In connection to this, a shooting occurred at the main house.<ref name=ilska>{{cite web|last1=Leino|first1=Per|title=All ilska riktades mot ordf\u00f6randen|trans-title=All anger was directed at the chairman|url=http://www.helagotland.se/start/?articleid=4555245|website=www.helagotland.se|publisher=Helagotland.se|accessdate=13 July 2015|date=2 December 2008|language=Swedish}}</ref> The museum and the estate are managed by the Brucebo Foundation.<ref name=SLU>{{cite web|last1=Sv\u00e4nnel|first1=Jessica|title=V\u00e5rdprogram f\u00f6r tr\u00e4dg\u00e5rden p\u00e5 Brucebo|url=http://jessicasvannel.se/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/V%C3%A5rdprogram-f%C3%B6r-Brucebo_12juni14_JessicaSv%C3%A4nnel.pdf|website=www.jessicasvannel.se|publisher=[[Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences]]|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> The foundation also grants scholarship to younger Canadian artists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brucebo and W.B. Bruce Fine Art Scholarships for Canadian Artists|url=http://www.swedenabroad.com/en-GB/Embassies/Ottawa/Study-in-Sweden/Scholarships/Brucebo-and-WB-Bruce-Fine-Art-Scholarships-2012-2013/|website=www.swedenabroad.com|publisher=[[List of diplomatic missions in Ottawa|Embassy of Sweden, Ottawa]]|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> In 1970, the {{convert|35|ha|km2|abbr=on}} Brucebo estate was established as a nature reserve.<ref name=blair>{{cite web|title=En William Blair kommer hem|trans-title=A William Blair comes home|url=http://www.lansstyrelsen.se/gotland/Sv/nyheter/2011/Pages/en-william-blair-kommer-hem.aspx?keyword=brucebo+naturreservat|website=www.lansstyrelsen.se|publisher=The County Administrative Boards of [[Gotland County]]|accessdate=14 July 2015|date=8 April 2011|language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery perrow=\"5\" widths=\"180\" heights=\"140\">\nFile:Brucebo salong.jpg|Brucebo artist's home, room with Bruce's portrait of his wife\nFile:Brucebo atelje s\u00f6der.jpg|The south part of the studio in Brucebo, Benedicks-Bruce's ''L'obs\u00e8de'' (left, back), ''Michel Angelo'' and bust of Bruce (right, front)\nFile:Brucebo atelje.jpg|The studio in Brucebo, Bruce's self portrait (left) and full figure portrait of his wife\nFile:Brucebo indianrummet.jpg|The \"Indian room\" at Brucebo with paintings from the Six Nations Reserve\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book\n| last1=Bruce\n| first1=William Blair\n| year=1982\n| title=Letters home, 1859\u20131906: the letters of William Blair Bruce\n| last2=Murray\n| first2=Joan\n| authorlink2=Joan Murray (art historian)\n| publisher=Penumbra Press\n| isbn=978-0-920806-36-4\n| url-access=registration\n| url=https://archive.org/details/lettershome185910000bruc\n}}\n\n*{{cite book \n|last1=Facos \n|first1=Michelle \n|editor-last=Bruce \n|editor-first=Tobi \n|title=Into the Light: The Paintings of William Blair Bruce (1859-1906) \n|date=2014 \n|publisher=Art Gallery of Hamilton, 2014 \n|isbn=1907804528 \n|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=HS8cngEACAAJ&dq=Into+the+Light:+The+Paintings+of+William+Blair+Bruce+(1859+-+1906).&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQqNDExNboAhXGOpoKHTcSArEQ6AEIKDAA\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|William Blair Bruce}}\n*[http://jessicasvannel.se/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/V%C3%A5rdprogram-f%C3%B6r-Brucebo_12juni14_JessicaSv%C3%A4nnel.pdf Maps, pictures and a presentation of Brucebo] (in Swedish)\n\n{{Canadian Impressionism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bruce, William Blair}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1906 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian male painters]]\n[[Category:People from Hamilton, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Canadian Impressionist painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in Sweden]]\n", "name_user": "Joan arden murray", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Blair_Bruce"}
{"title_page": "Recycling symbol", "text_new": "{{short description|Symbol used to designate recyclable materials}}\n{{More footnotes|date=April 2009}}\n{{Short lead|date=August 2018}}\n{{special characters}}<!-- I saw boxes instead of special characters. -->\n[[File:Recycle001.svg|thumb|right|The Universal Recycling Symbol, here rendered with a black outline and green fill. Both filled and outline versions of the symbol are in use.]]\nThe universal '''recycling symbol''' ({{Unichar|2672|Universal recycling symbol}} or {{Unichar|267B|Black universal recycling symbol}} in [[Unicode]]) is internationally recognized for [[recycling]] activity.\n\n==History==\nWorldwide attention to environmental issues led to the first [[Earth Day]] in 1970<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liveabout.com/the-history-of-earth-day-1203691|title=The History and Importance of Earth Day|last=West|first=Larry|website=LiveAbout|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>. [[Container Corporation of America]], a large producer of recycled paperboard, sponsored a contest for art and design students at high schools and colleges across the country to raise awareness of environmental issues. It was won by [[Gary Anderson (designer)|Gary Anderson]], then a 23-year-old college student at the [[University of Southern California]], whose entry was the image now known as the universal recycling symbol.<ref name=GaryFound>{{cite journal|last=Jones|first=Penny|author2=Jerry Powell |title=Gary Anderson has been found!|journal=Resource Recycling: North America's Recycling and Composting Journal|date=May 1999|pages=pg.1\u20132|url=http://logoblink.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/03/recycling_symbol_garyanderson.pdf|accessdate=2011-05-26}}</ref> The symbol is not [[trademark]]ed and is in the [[public domain]].<ref name=GaryFound/> The public-domain status of the symbol has been challenged, but this challenge was unsuccessful owing to the wide use of the symbol. However, the universal symbol may have been inspired by similar existing recycling symbols, such as one featuring two arrows chasing each other in a circle that Volkswagen stamped in the early 1960s into some automobile parts it remanufactured{{citation_needed|date=September 2018}}.\n\n==Variants==\nThe recycling symbol is in the [[public domain]], and is not a [[trademark]]. The Container Corporation of America originally applied for a trademark on the design, but the application was challenged, and the corporation decided to abandon the claim.<ref name=\"GaryFound\"/> As such, anyone may use or modify the recycling symbol, royalty-free.\n\nThough use of the symbol is regulated by law in some countries,<ref name=RulesLogo>{{cite web|title=Rules Governing Use of Recycling Logo|url=http://www.recyclingexpert.co.uk/rules-governing-use-recycling-logo.html|work=Recycling Expert [website]|publisher=recyclingexpert.co.uk|accessdate=2011-05-16}}</ref>  countless variants of it exist worldwide. Anderson's original proposal had the arrows form a triangle standing on its tip\u2014upside down compared with the versions most commonly seen today\u2014but the CCA, in adopting Anderson's design, rotated it 60\u00b0 to stand on its base instead.<ref name=\"GaryFound\"/>\n\nBoth Anderson's proposal and CCA's designs form a [[M\u00f6bius strip]] with ''one'' half-twist by having two of the arrows fold over each other, and one fold under, thereby canceling out one of the other folds. However, most variants of the symbol used today have all the arrows folding over themselves, producing a M\u00f6bius strip with ''three'' half-twists. Existing single half-twist variants of the logo do not generally agree on which of the arrows is the one to fold underneath.  The logo is usually displayed with the arrows circulating clockwise, but the underlying M\u00f6bius strip exists in two [[topology|topologically]] distinct mirror-image forms of opposite [[handedness]].\n\nThe [[American Paper Institute]] originally promoted four different variants of the recycling symbol for different purposes. The plain M\u00f6bius loop, either white with an outline or solid black, was to be used to indicate that a product was ''recyclable''.  The other two variants had the M\u00f6bius loop inside a circle\u2014either [[white on black]] or black on white\u2014and were meant for products ''made of recycled materials'', with the white-on-black version to be used for 100% recycled fiber, and the black-on-white version for products containing both recycled and unrecycled fiber.<ref name=\"GaryFound\"/> For example, a paper envelope might have both the first and last of these four symbols, to indicate that it was recyclable, and made from both recycled and unrecycled fibers.\n\nIn addition to the [[resin identification code]]s 1\u20137 in the triangular recycling symbol, Unicode lists the following recycling symbols:\n* {{unichar|2672|UNIVERSAL RECYCLING SYMBOL}}\n* {{unichar|267A|RECYCLING SYMBOL FOR GENERIC MATERIALS}}\n* {{unichar|267B|BLACK UNIVERSAL RECYCLING SYMBOL}}\n* {{unichar|267C|RECYCLED PAPER SYMBOL}} (indicates product contains recycled paper)\n* {{unichar|267D|PARTIALLY-RECYCLED PAPER SYMBOL}} (indicates product contains partially recycled paper)\n* {{unichar|267E|PERMANENT PAPER SIGN}} (e.g. for [[acid-free paper]])\n\nAn ISO/IEC working group has researched and documented some of the variations of the recycling logo currently{{when|date=June 2012}} in use, and has made recommendations for adding some more of them to the Unicode standard.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Everson|first1=Michael (co-editor)|title=Background information on Recycling Symbols|url=http://std.dkuug.dk/jtc1/sc2/wg2/docs/n2342.pdf|work=ISO/IEC JTC1/SC2/WG2 N2342|publisher=ISO/IEC|accessdate=2011-05-26|first2=Asmus|last2=Freytag (co-editor)}}</ref>\n\nWith the rapid expansion of materials converted to [[printer filament]] for [[3-D printing]] using [[recyclebot]] technology, a large expansion of resin identification codes has been proposed.<ref>Emily J. Hunt, Chenlong Zhang, Nick Anzalone, Joshua M. Pearce, [https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.resconrec.2015.02.004 Polymer recycling codes for distributed manufacturing with 3-D printers], ''Resources, Conservation and Recycling'', '''97''', pp. 24\u201330 (2015). [https://www.academia.edu/11229348/Polymer_recycling_codes_for_distributed_manufacturing_with_3-D_printers open access]</ref>\n\n==Resin identification code==\n{{main|Recycling codes}}\nIn 1988, the American [[Society of the Plastics Industry]] (SPI) developed the [[resin identification code]] which is used to indicate the predominant plastic material used in the manufacture of the product or packaging.  Their purpose is to assist recyclers with sorting the collected materials, but they do not necessarily mean that the product/packaging can be recycled either through domestic curbside collection or industrial collections.  The SPI symbols are loosely based on the M\u00f6bius loop symbol, but feature simpler bent (rather than folded over) arrows that can be embossed on plastic surfaces without loss of detail.  The arrows are formed into a flat, two-dimensional triangle rather than the pseudo-three-dimensional triangle used in the original recycling logo.\n\nThe different resin identification codes can be represented by [[Unicode]] icons <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\u2673</span> (U+2673), <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\u2674</span> (U+2674), <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\u2675</span> (U+2675), <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\u2676</span> (U+2676), <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\u2677</span> (U+2677), <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\u2678</span> (U+2678), <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\u2679</span> (U+2679), and <span style=\"font-size:87%;\">\u267a</span> (U+267A).\n\n[[Recycling codes]] extend these numbers above 7 to include various non-plastic materials, including metals, glass, paper, and batteries of various types.\n\n==Other variants==\n[[File:Recycle symbol Taiwan.svg|thumb|[[Taiwan]]'s recycling symbol features the use of [[negative space]] to also create arrows pointing outward]]\n\u267e, an [[infinity]] sign (\u221e) inside a circle, represents the '''permanent paper symbol''',  used in packaging and publishing to signify the use of durable [[acid-free paper]].   In some ways, this logo expresses the ''opposite'' intention from the recycle logo, in that the acid-free paper is intended to last indefinitely, rather than being recycled.  Nevertheless, acid-free paper does not usually contain toxic materials (although certain inks do), so it is easily recycled or composted.\n\nA satirical version of the classic recycling logo also exists, in which the three arrows are twisted from a circular pattern to pointing radially outward, thus symbolizing wasteful one-time usage rather than environmentally friendly recycling.  This message is reinforced by the circular inscription, \"THIS PROJECT WAS ENVIRONMENTALLY UNFRIENDLY\", surrounding the modified logo.  The satirical logo appears in the 1998 catalog of an [[installation art]] work in [[Bayonne, New Jersey]], in which the artist [[Steven Pippin]] modified a row of glass-doored washing machines in a [[laundromat]] to operate as giant cameras.  The cameras were used to take sequential photographs in the manner of pioneering [[stop motion]] photographer [[Eadweard Muybridge]].  The front-loading washing machines were then used to develop and process the 24&nbsp;inch (61&nbsp;cm) diameter circular film negatives.<ref name=LaundroLoco>{{cite book|last=Pippin|first=Steven John|author2=San Francisco Museum of Modern Art|title=Laundromat locomotion : Mr. Pippin : [on the occasion of the Exhibition Laundromat Locomotion]|year=1998|publisher=Verlag der Kunst|location=[Amsterdam ; Dresden]|isbn=978-90-5705-094-7|type=Softcover}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Green Dot (symbol)|Green Dot symbol]]\n* [[List of international common standards]]\n* [[Japanese recycling symbols]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Jones, Penny; Powell, Jerry. \"[http://logoblink.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/03/recycling_symbol_garyanderson.pdf Gary Anderson has been found!]\". ''Resource Recycling: North America's Recycling and Composting Journal'', May 1999.\n* Everson, Michael; Freytag, Asmus (2001-04-02). [http://std.dkuug.dk/jtc1/sc2/wg2/docs/n2342.pdf \"Background information on Recycling Symbols\" (PDF)], [[International Organization for Standardization|ISO]]/[[International Electrotechnical Commission|IEC]] Working Group Document N2342\n* [http://logoblink.com/44-recycle-logos/ 44 Recycle Logos and Symbols]\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Recycling symbols}}\n\n[[Category:Certification marks]]\n[[Category:Consumer symbols]]\n[[Category:Recycling]]\n[[Category:Symbols introduced in 1970]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Symbol used to designate recyclable materials}}\n{{More footnotes|date=April 2009}}\n{{Short lead|date=August 2018}}\n{{special characters}}<!-- I saw boxes instead of special characters. -->\n[[File:Recycle001.svg|thumb|right|The Universal Recycling Symbol, here rendered with a black outline and green fill. Both filled and outline versions of the symbol are in use.]]\nThe universal '''recycling symbol''' ({{Unichar|2672|Universal recycling symbol}} or {{Unichar|267B|Black universal recycling symbol}} in [[Unicode]]) is internationally recognized for [[recycling]] activity.\n\n==History==\nWorldwide attention to environmental issues led to the first [[Earth Day]] in 1970<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liveabout.com/the-history-of-earth-day-1203691|title=The History and Importance of Earth Day|last=West|first=Larry|website=LiveAbout|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>. [[Container Corporation of America]], a large producer of recycled paperboard, sponsored a contest for art and design students at high schools and colleges across the country to raise awareness of environmental issues. It was won by [[Gary Anderson (designer)|Gary Anderson]], then a 23-year-old college student at the [[University of Southern California]], whose entry was the image now known as the universal recycling symbol.<ref name=GaryFound>{{cite journal|last=Jones|first=Penny|author2=Jerry Powell |title=Gary Anderson has been found!|journal=Resource Recycling: North America's Recycling and Composting Journal|date=May 1999|pages=pg.1\u20132|url=http://logoblink.com/wp-content/uploads/2008/03/recycling_symbol_garyanderson.pdf|accessdate=2011-05-26}}</ref> The symbol is not [[trademark]]ed and is in the [[public domain]].<ref name=GaryFound/> The public-domain status of the symbol has been challenged, but this challenge was unsuccessful owing to the wide use of the symbol. However, the universal symbol may have been inspired by similar existing recycling symbols, such as one featuring two arrows chasing each other in a circle that Volkswagen stamped in the early 1960s into some automobile parts it remanufactured{{citation_needed|date=September 2018}}.\n\n==Variants==\nThe recycling symbol is in the [[public domain]], and is not a [[trademark]]. The Container Corporation of America originally applied for a trademark on the design, but the application was challenged, and the corporation decided to abandon the claim.<ref name=\"GaryFound\"/> As such, anyone may use or modify the recycling symbol, royalty-free.\n\nThough use of the symbol is regulated by law in some countries,<ref name=RulesLogo>{{cite web|title=Rules Governing Use of Recycling Logo|url=http://www.recyclingexpert.co.uk/rules-governing-use-recycling-logo.html|work=Recycling Expert [website]|publisher=recyclingexpert.co.uk|accessdate=2011-05-16}}</ref>  countless variants of it exist worldwide. Anderson's original proposal had the arrows form a triangle standing on its tip\u2014upside down compared with the versions most commonly seen today\u2014but the CCA, in adopting Anderson's design, rotated it 60\u00b0 to stand on its base instead.<ref name=\"GaryFound\"/>\n\nBoth