Anonymous Rex (novel)|Anonymous Rex]]'' by [[Eric Garcia (writer)|Eric Garcia]] (2000)\n*''The Lion of Cormarre and Other Stories: The Collected Stories of [[Arthur C. Clarke]] (1937\u20131949)'' (2001)\n*''Mimus'' by Lilli Thal (2007)\n*''Spud'' by [[John van de Ruit]] (2008)\n*''Sebastian Darke: Prince of Fools'' by [[Philip Caveney]] (2008)\n*''Spud: The Madness Continues'' by [[John van de Ruit]] (2009)\n*''[[The War of the Worlds]]'' by [[H. G. Wells]] (2012)\n\n=== Video games ===\n\n* ''[[James Bond 007: Nightfire]]'' (2002) as [[James Bond (literary character)|James Bond]]\n* [[Eragon (video game)|''Eragon'']] (2006) as Brom\n\n==Discography==\n\n* 1982: \"Charades\" on the ''[[Grease 2 (soundtrack)|Grease 2]]'' soundtrack (as Michael Carrington)\n* 1982: \"(Love Will) Turn Back the Hands of Time\" with [[Michelle Pfeiffer]] on the ''[[Grease 2 (soundtrack)|Grease 2]]'' soundtrack\n* 1982: \"Who's That Guy?\" with Cast on the ''[[Grease 2 (soundtrack)|Grease 2]]'' soundtrack\n* 1982: \"Reproduction\" with Cast on the ''[[Grease 2 (soundtrack)|Grease 2]]'' soundtrack\n* 1982: \"Rock-A-Hula-Luau (Summer is Coming)\" with Cast on the ''[[Grease 2 (soundtrack)|Grease 2]]'' soundtrack\n* 1982: \"We'll Be Together\" with Cast on the ''[[Grease 2 (soundtrack)|Grease 2]]'' soundtrack\n* 1995: \"Say No More (Mon Amore)\" in Alan Moyle's ''[[Empire Records]]'' (as Rex Manning)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n* [[Theater World Award]] (1979) for his performance in ''Class Enemy'' ([[Players Theatre]], [[West Village]], New York City).<ref name=\"broadway\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0001028}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|14561}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caulfield, Maxwell}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:English people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:American male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:English male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:People from Belper]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStage credits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maxwell_Caulfield"}
{"title_page": "Ak-Sar-Ben (arena)", "text_new": "{{Infobox stadium\n| name                = Ak-Sar-Ben Race Track<br>and Coliseum\n| nickname            = \n| logo_image          = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = Ak-Sar-Ben 19930325.jpg\n| caption             = Aerial view of the facility in 1993\n| fullname            = \n| former names        = \n| location            = 6800 Mercy Road<br>[[Omaha, Nebraska]], U.S. <!--68196-2627-->\n| coordinates         = {{coord|41.240|N|96.013|W|type:landmark|display=it}}\n| broke_ground        = \n| built               = \n| opened              = {{Start date|1919|07|06}} <small>(Race track)</small><br>{{Start date|1929|06|09}} <small>(Coliseum)</small>\n| renovated           = 1921, 1938, 1965, 1986\n| expanded            = 1928, 1975\n| closed              = {{End date|1995|08|08}} <small>(Race track)</small><br>{{nowrap|{{End date|2002|09}} <small>(Coliseum)</small>}}\n| demolished          = {{End date|2004|10|08}}\n| owner               = [[Knights of Ak-Sar-Ben|Ak-Sar-Ben Future Trust]]<br>[[Douglas County, Nebraska|Douglas County]]\n| operator            = \n| surface             = \n| scoreboard          = \n| cost                = [[United States dollar|$]]1 million<br><small>(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|US|1000000|1919}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}})</small>\n| architect           = \n| project_manager     = \n| structural engineer = \n| services engineer   = \n| general_contractor  = \n| main_contractors    = \n| capacity            = 11,500 <small>(Grandstand)</small><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;7,200 <small>(Coliseum)</small>\n| suites              = \n| record_attendance   = \n| dimensions          = \n| acreage             = \n| volume              = \n| tenants             = [[Omaha Knights (AHA)|Omaha Knights]] ([[United States Hockey League (1945&ndash;1951)|USHL]]) (1945&ndash;1951)<br>[[Omaha Knights]] ([[International Hockey League (1945\u20132001)|IHL]]/[[Central Professional Hockey League|CHL]]) (1959\u20131965, 1966&ndash;1975)<br>[[Omaha Racers]] ([[Continental Basketball Association|CBA]]) (1989\u20131997)<br>[[Omaha Lancers]] ([[United States Hockey League|USHL]]) (1990&ndash;2002)\n| embedded            =\n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| publictransit       =\n}}\n{{Location map\n|USA\n|relief     = 1\n|label      = <small>Omaha</small>\n|lat        = 41.240\n|long       = -96.013\n|caption    = Location in the [[United States]]\n|marksize   = 5\n|position   = bottom \n|float      = \n|background = \n|width      = 230\n}}\n{{Location map\n|USA Nebraska\n|relief     = 1\n|label      = <small>Omaha</small>\n|lat        = 41.240\n|long       = -96.013\n|caption    = Location in [[Nebraska]]\n|marksize   = 5\n|position   = left\n|float      = \n|background = \n|width      = 200\n}}\nThe '''Ak-Sar-Ben Race Track and Coliseum''' was an [[indoor arena]] and [[thoroughbred horse race|horse racing]] complex in the central [[United States]], located in [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]], [[Nebraska]].\n\nBuilt to fund the civic and philanthropic activities of the [[Knights of Ak-Sar-Ben]], the [[thoroughbred]] race track was built in 1919,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historicomaha.com/aksarben.htm |title=Ak-Sar-Ben Race Track and Coliseum |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=HistoricOmaha.com |publisher= |accessdate=November 5, 2013}}</ref> and the Coliseum in 1929. The racetrack closed in 1995 and the arena in 2002; the facility was demolished in 2005, and is currently being redeveloped for a variety of uses, including dormitory housing for the [[University of Nebraska Omaha]] and the [[Aksarben Village]] development.\n\nAk-Sar-Ben is \"Nebraska\" spelled backwards.  The Knights originally said they were turning Nebraska around, thus \"Ak-Sar-Ben.\"\n\n==History==\n===Coliseum=== \nAk-Sar-Ben Coliseum was the premiere [[ice rink]] and [[concert]] [[arena]] in Omaha for more than 70 years. Popular acts ranging from [[Frank Sinatra]] to [[Elvis Presley]] to [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] all performed to sold-out crowds.  It was also home to the [[Omaha Knights]], a [[minor league]] [[ice hockey|hockey]] team from 1959 to 1975. The Knights began operations in 1959 in the [[International Hockey League (1945&ndash;2001)|IHL]], and later moved to the now-defunct [[Central Hockey League (1963&ndash;1984)|CHL]], with teams affiliated with the [[National Hockey League|NHL's]] [[Montreal Canadiens]], [[New York Rangers]], and both the [[Calgary Flames|Calgary and Atlanta Flames]].  The arena hosted the [[United States Hockey League|USHL]]'s [[Omaha Lancers]] for its final dozen years and the [[Omaha Racers]] [[basketball]] of the [[Continental Basketball Association|CBA]] from 1989 to 1997.<ref>{{cite news|title=History of the Continental Basketball Association|url=http://hometown.aol.com/bradleyrd/cba7801.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wowt.com/sports/headlines/Omaha-Racers-Reunite-20-Years-After-Winning-CBA-Title-220952401.html |title=Omaha Racers Reunite 20 Years After Winning CBA Title |last1=Jernstrom |first1=Ross |last2= |first2= |date=August 24, 2013 |website=[[WOWT]] |publisher=[[Gray Television]] |accessdate=November 5, 2013}}</ref> The Coliseum also hosted world-class [[boxing]], was a major stop on the [[Professional Bull Riders|PBR]] and attracted many popular comedians.\n\n===Horse racing===\nIn the racetrack's glory days, the Coliseum housed a cinema-sized screen and betting windows to handle the overflow of fans. In the mid-1980s, Ak-Sar-Ben was tenth in the nation in racetrack attendance, with up to 25,000 betting $2 million per day on weekends. Many festivals were also held in the Coliseum annually, including a Greek Festival and River City Roundup booths.\n\nFollowing his death in 1959, the 1935 [[Triple Crown of Thoroughbred Racing|Triple Crown]] winner [[Omaha (horse)|Omaha]] was buried at the racetrack's Circle of Champions.  The [[thoroughbred]] spent his final nine years at a farm outside of [[Nebraska City, Nebraska|Nebraska City]] and made promotional appearances at the Ak-Sar-Ben racetrack during the 1950s.\n\n==Closure and demolition==\nHorse racing at Ak-Sar-Ben ended in August 1995, just ten years after its record season of 1985. [[Dog racing]] began in adjacent [[Iowa]] in 1986 and other forms of gambling followed, and attendance rapidly declined at Ak-Sar-Ben. A portion of the property was sold to First Data Resources under the agreement that FDR would donate part of the land to the [[University of Nebraska Omaha]] (UNO) for its Aksarben Campus to build a new College of Information and Technology.<ref>(nd) [http://www.ist.unomaha.edu/ College of Information and Technology].</ref>\n\nAfter the remaining buildings and grandstand were torn down in early 2005, a proposal was put forth to create a mixed-use development called [[Aksarben Village]].<ref>(nd) [http://www.aksarbenvillage.com  Aksarben Village]. Retrieved 7/17/07.</ref> Construction began in 2006 and the first businesses opened in 2008.<ref>http://www.allbusiness.com/real-estate/commercial-residential-property-commercial/12149041-1.html</ref>  [[Baxter Arena]], home to several of UNO's sports teams, opened in October 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.omaha.com/news/metro/uno-s-rising-arena-finances-both-solid/article_c1e9bd99-ae9c-51cc-872e-281c53255a87.html |title=UNO's rising arena, finances both solid |first=Christopher |last=Burbach |newspaper=[[Omaha World-Herald]] |date=October 6, 2014 |accessdate=February 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the closure of the racetrack, simulcast facility Horsemen's Park ({{coord|41.204|-96.011}}) was opened near [[Ralston, Nebraska|Ralston]] {{nowrap|in 1998.<ref name=hpabtus>{{cite web|url=https://www.horsemenspark.com/about-us |work=Horsemen's Park |title=About us |accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref>}} The horse racing industry in Nebraska is now confined to live racing dates rotating from Fonner Park in [[Grand Island, Nebraska|Grand Island]], to the Lincoln Race Course in [[Lincoln, Nebraska|Lincoln]], and finishing at Agricultural Park in [[Columbus, Nebraska|Columbus]], plus a four-day meet at Horsemen's Park (the latter required to keep their simulcasting license).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.horsemenspark.com/live_racing.asp |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-01-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100226175130/http://www.horsemenspark.com/live_racing.asp |archive-date=2010-02-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  A fourth track, Atokad in the northeast part of the state, also holds a brief meeting each year.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Culture in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n* [[Sports in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ak-sar-ben.com Historic - Ak-Sar-Ben Race Track and Coliseum]\n* [https://www.usatoday.com/sports/horses/2008-04-18-3724553517_x.htm USA Today] - Horse racing fights for survival in [[Nebraska]] - 18-Apr-2008\n\n{{Aksarben}}\n{{Music venues of Nebraska}}\n\n[[Category:Organizations based in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Defunct indoor arenas in the United States]]\n[[Category:Indoor ice hockey venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Omaha Ak-Sar-Ben Knights]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Horse racing venues in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Defunct horse racing venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of Midtown Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Former buildings and structures in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Demolished sports venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct sports venues in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Demolished buildings and structures in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:1919 establishments in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:2002 disestablishments in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Indoor arenas in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1919]]\n[[Category:Sports venues demolished in 2004]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox stadium\n| name                = Ak-Sar-Ben Race Track<br>and Coliseum\n| nickname            = \n| logo_image          = \n| logo_caption        = \n| image               = Ak-Sar-Ben 19930325.jpg\n| caption             = Aerial view of the facility in 1993\n| fullname            = \n| former names        = \n| location            = 6800 Mercy Road<br>[[Omaha, Nebraska]], U.S. <!--68196-2627-->\n| coordinates         = {{coord|41.240|N|96.013|W|type:landmark|display=it}}\n| broke_ground        = \n| built               = \n| opened              = {{Start date|1919|07|06}} <small>(Race track)</small><br>{{Start date|1929|06|09}} <small>(Coliseum)</small>\n| renovated           = 1921, 1938, 1965, 1986\n| expanded            = 1928, 1975\n| closed              = {{End date|1995|08|08}} <small>(Race track)</small><br>{{nowrap|{{End date|2002|09}} <small>(Coliseum)</small>}}\n| demolished          = {{End date|2004|10|08}}\n| owner               = [[Knights of Ak-Sar-Ben|Ak-Sar-Ben Future Trust]]<br>[[Douglas County, Nebraska|Douglas County]]\n| operator            = \n| surface             = \n| scoreboard          = \n| cost                = [[United States dollar|$]]1 million<br><small>(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|US|1000000|1919}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}})</small>\n| architect           = \n| project_manager     = \n| structural engineer = \n| services engineer   = \n| general_contractor  = \n| main_contractors    = \n| capacity            = 11,500 <small>(Grandstand)</small><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;7,200 <small>(Coliseum)</small>\n| suites              = \n| record_attendance   = \n| dimensions          = \n| acreage             = \n| volume              = \n| tenants             = [[Omaha Knights (AHA)|Omaha Knights]] ([[United States Hockey League (1945&ndash;1951)|USHL]]) (1945&ndash;1951)<br>[[Omaha Knights]] ([[International Hockey League (1945\u20132001)|IHL]]/[[Central Professional Hockey League|CHL]]) (1959\u20131965, 1966&ndash;1975)<br>[[Omaha Racers]] ([[Continental Basketball A