old-out crowds.  It was also home to the [[Omaha Knights]], a [[minor league]] [[ice hockey|hockey]] team from 1959 to 1975. The Knights began operations in 1959 in the [[International Hockey League (1945&ndash;2001)|IHL]], and later moved to the now-defunct [[Central Hockey League (1963&ndash;1984)|CHL]], with teams affiliated with the [[National Hockey League|NHL's]] [[Montreal Canadiens]], [[New York Rangers]], and both the [[Calgary Flames|Calgary and Atlanta Flames]].  The arena hosted the [[United States Hockey League|USHL]]'s [[Omaha Lancers]] for its final dozen years and the [[Omaha Racers]] [[basketball]] of the [[Continental Basketball Association|CBA]] from 1989 to 1997.<ref>{{cite news|title=History of the Continental Basketball Association|url=http://hometown.aol.com/bradleyrd/cba7801.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wowt.com/sports/headlines/Omaha-Racers-Reunite-20-Years-After-Winning-CBA-Title-220952401.html |title=Omaha Racers Reunite 20 Years After Winning CBA Title |last1=Jernstrom |first1=Ross |last2= |first2= |date=August 24, 2013 |website=[[WOWT]] |publisher=[[Gray Television]] |accessdate=November 5, 2013}}</ref> The Coliseum also hosted world-class [[boxing]], was a major stop on the [[Professional Bull Riders|PBR]] and attracted many popular comedians.\n\n===Horse racing===\nIn the racetrack's glory days, the Coliseum housed a cinema-sized screen and betting windows to handle the overflow of fans. In the mid-1980s, Ak-Sar-Ben was tenth in the nation in racetrack attendance, with up to 25,000 betting $2 million per day on weekends. Many festivals were also held in the Coliseum annually, including a Greek Festival and River City Roundup booths.\n\nFollowing his death in 1959, the 1935 [[Triple Crown of Thoroughbred Racing|Triple Crown]] winner [[Omaha (horse)|Omaha]] was buried at the racetrack's Circle of Champions.  The [[thoroughbred]] spent his final nine years at a farm outside of [[Nebraska City, Nebraska|Nebraska City]] and made promotional appearances at the Ak-Sar-Ben racetrack during the 1950s.\n\n==Closure and demolition==\nHorse racing at Ak-Sar-Ben ended in August 1995, just ten years after its record season of 1985. [[Dog racing]] began in adjacent [[Iowa]] in 1986 and other forms of gambling followed, and attendance rapidly declined at Ak-Sar-Ben. A portion of the property was sold to First Data Resources under the agreement that FDR would donate part of the land to the [[University of Nebraska Omaha]] (UNO) for its Aksarben Campus to build a new College of Information and Technology.<ref>(nd) [http://www.ist.unomaha.edu/ College of Information and Technology].</ref>\n\nAfter the remaining buildings and grandstand were torn down in early 2005, a proposal was put forth to create a mixed-use development called [[Aksarben Village]].<ref>(nd) [http://www.aksarbenvillage.com  Aksarben Village]. Retrieved 7/17/07.</ref> Construction began in 2006 and the first businesses opened in 2008.<ref>http://www.allbusiness.com/real-estate/commercial-residential-property-commercial/12149041-1.html</ref>  [[Baxter Arena]], home to several of UNO's sports teams, opened in October 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.omaha.com/news/metro/uno-s-rising-arena-finances-both-solid/article_c1e9bd99-ae9c-51cc-872e-281c53255a87.html |title=UNO's rising arena, finances both solid |first=Christopher |last=Burbach |newspaper=[[Omaha World-Herald]] |date=October 6, 2014 |accessdate=February 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the closure of the racetrack, simulcast facility Horsemen's Park ({{coord|41.204|-96.011}}) was opened near [[Ralston, Nebraska|Ralston]] {{nowrap|in 1998.<ref name=hpabtus>{{cite web|url=https://www.horsemenspark.com/about-us |work=Horsemen's Park |title=About us |accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref>}} The horse racing industry in Nebraska is now confined to live racing dates rotating from Fonner Park in [[Grand Island, Nebraska|Grand Island]], to the Lincoln Race Course in [[Lincoln, Nebraska|Lincoln]], and finishing at Agricultural Park in [[Columbus, Nebraska|Columbus]], plus a four-day meet at Horsemen's Park (the latter required to keep their simulcasting license).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.horsemenspark.com/live_racing.asp |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-01-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100226175130/http://www.horsemenspark.com/live_racing.asp |archive-date=2010-02-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Culture in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n* [[Sports in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ak-sar-ben.com Historic - Ak-Sar-Ben Race Track and Coliseum]\n* [https://www.usatoday.com/sports/horses/2008-04-18-3724553517_x.htm USA Today] - Horse racing fights for survival in [[Nebraska]] - 18-Apr-2008\n\n{{Aksarben}}\n{{Music venues of Nebraska}}\n\n[[Category:Organizations based in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Defunct indoor arenas in the United States]]\n[[Category:Indoor ice hockey venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Omaha Ak-Sar-Ben Knights]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Horse racing venues in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Defunct horse racing venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of Midtown Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Former buildings and structures in Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Demolished sports venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct sports venues in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Demolished buildings and structures in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:1919 establishments in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:2002 disestablishments in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Indoor arenas in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1919]]\n[[Category:Sports venues demolished in 2004]]\n", "name_user": "Tom Barrister 2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClosure and demolition:adding information.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ak-Sar-Ben_(arena)"}
